.TH GWSIM 1
.SH NAME
gwsim \- Greaseweazle device simulator for gw2dmk, dmk2gw, and gwhist
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B gwsim
[\fIoptions\fP]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B gwsim
emulates a Greaseweazle flux-imaging device with attached floppy
drives whose diskettes are backed by DMK image files.  It serves the
Greaseweazle serial protocol on a pseudo-terminal, so the unmodified
host tools connect to it exactly as to real hardware:
.PP
.RS
gwsim &
.br
gw2dmk \-G ./gwsim-pty out.dmk
.RE
.PP
The simulator is functionally accurate rather than cycle accurate.
Seek, motor spin-up, and rotational latencies track wall time
(within a few percent) unless
.B \-\-fast
is given, in which case all delays are skipped; the flux data
produced is identical either way.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-m, \-\-model \fImodel\fP
Greaseweazle model to emulate:
.B f7
(default) or
.BR v4.1 .
The models differ only in the identity reported by CMD_GET_INFO.
.TP
.B \-f, \-\-fast
Skip all simulated delays.
.TP
.B \-p, \-\-pty-link \fIpath\fP
Where to place the symlink to the pty device [./gwsim-pty].
.TP
.B \-s, \-\-socket \fIpath\fP
UNIX-domain control socket [./gwsim.sock]; \fBnone\fP disables it.
.TP
.B \-D, \-\-drive \fIN\fP:\fItype\fP[,\fIoption\fP...]
Attach a drive at unit \fIN\fP (0\-2).  May be repeated.  If no
drive is given, a 5.25" DD drive is attached at unit 0.
Drive types and defaults:
.RS
.TP
.B 8sd, 8dd
8" single/double density; 77 tracks, 360 RPM (the spindle turns
whenever the drive is powered), attached through an FDADAP 50-to-34
pin adapter.
.TP
.B 525sd
5.25" single density; 35 tracks, 300 RPM.
.TP
.B 525dd
5.25" double density; 40 tracks, 300 RPM.
.TP
.B 525qd
5.25" quad density (96 tpi); 80 tracks, 300 RPM.
.TP
.B 525hd
5.25" high density; 80 tracks, 360 RPM (300 selectable).
.TP
.B 35dd, 35hd
3.5" double/high density; 80 tracks, 300 RPM.
.RE
.IP
Options: \fBtracks=\fIT\fR, \fBrpm=\fI300|360\fR (where the type
supports both), \fBsides=\fI1|2\fR, \fBfdadap\fP (implied for 8"
types), and \fBwp\fP (force write protect).
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-insert \fIN\fP:\fIfile\fP
Insert diskette image \fIfile\fP into unit \fIN\fP at startup.
.TP
.B \-l, \-\-list
List supported Greaseweazle models and drive types.
.SH CONTROL COMMANDS
The following commands are accepted on standard input and on the
control socket while the simulator runs:
.TP
.B insert \fIunit\fP \fIfile\fP
Insert a diskette image.
.TP
.B eject \fIunit\fP
Remove the diskette, flushing any writes back to the file.
.TP
.B wp \fIunit\fP on|off
Force or release write protection.
.TP
.B status
Show the emulated device, drives, and media.
.TP
.B quit
Shut down (also flushes written media).
.SH MEDIA
Diskette images are DMK files, read and written with the same
conventions as gw2dmk and dmk2gw.  The media's data rate is derived
from the DMK track length and the drive's rotational speed, so a
standard DD image in a 300 RPM drive presents as 250 kbps and the
same image in a 360 RPM 5.25" HD drive presents as 300 kbps, just
as with real hardware.  A DMK is write-protected if its header
write-protect byte is set or the file is not writable.
.SH BUSES
The host tool selects the bus type at runtime: on the IBM PC bus
two units are addressable (drives \fBa\fP and \fBb\fP); on the
Shugart bus, three (\fB0\fP\-\fB2\fP).  8" drives sit behind an
emulated FDADAP adapter.
.SH LIMITATIONS
The simulator does not appear on the USB bus, so the host tools'
device autodetection cannot find it; always pass \fB\-G\fP.
Reading an unformatted track or the far side of a single-sided
diskette returns random flux.  Linux only.
.SH SEE ALSO
gw2dmk(1), dmk2gw(1), gwhist(1)
